What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am most interested in what features are best for predicting borrowersAPR. What is tricky about this is that a lot of our statistics are set by the borrowerAPR. For example Lender Yield is obviosuly staiscially dependent on borrower APR and we do not need statiscal evidence to understand this. Therefore I will be looking for variabls that are separate from this. My guess is that APR is set off propser rating and prosper rating is there to take into account catorgorical variables such as employment and income range etc.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect that Prospers rating system will have the strongest correlation with the APR but it is then important to observe what predicts the Prospers rating to manfacture a strong understanding of this dataset.

In [17]:
def bivaraite_countplot_order(df, x, y, order):
    sb.barplot(data=df, x=x, y=y, color=base_color, order=order)
    plt.xlabel(x)
    plt.ylabel(y);

def bivaraite_countplot(df, x, y):
    sb.barplot(data=df, x=x, y=y, color=base_color)
    plt.xlabel(x)
    plt.ylabel(y);
    
def bivaraite_countplot_order_xrot(x, y, order):
    plt.xticks(rotation=35)
    sb.barplot(data=df, x=x, y=y, color=base_color, order=order)
    plt.xlabel(x)
    plt.ylabel(y);
    
def scatter_bivariate(variable_y, variable_x):
    sb.regplot(data = df, x = variable_x, y = variable_y);
    plt.xlabel(variable_x)
    plt.ylabel(variable_y);

def univariate_countplot(variable):
    counts = df[variable].value_counts()
    order = counts.index
    return sb.countplot(data = df, y = variable, order = order, color=base_color);

Clearly debt has a negative correlation with ProsperScore and income has a postive one. When it came to employment status exploration I conlcuded that thedistriubution of the dataset on this front was not suitable for us to draw any conlusions from.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

After controlling for homeownership I found that the relationship betwen ProsperScore with debt and income respectively is the same. Hence we can conclude from this that the there is strong negative relationship betwen debt and ProsperScore and a strong postive one with income range, therefore because of what we have conlcuded concerning ProsperScore and borrower APR we can then extend the abovementioned relationships onto to APR. Stating that with higher debt to income ratios borrowers should expect higher APR rates and lower rates for higher incomes.
